<problem>
<variantControl nVariants='1' />
<title>Tangent line to alpha function</title>

<setup>

<function name='g' variables='n t' simplify='full' symbolic>t^n*e^(1-t)</function>
<function name='g1' variables='t' >$$g(1,t)</function>

<function name='gprime' variables='n t' simplify='full' symbolic>e^(1 - t) (n - t) t^(-1 + n)</function>
<function name='g1prime' variables='t' simplify='full'>e^(1-t) (1-t)</function>
<math name='L10' simplify="numbers">$$g1(0)+$$g1prime(0)*(t-0)</math>
<math name='L11' simplify="numbers">$$g1(1)+$$g1prime(1)*(t-1)</math>
<number name='g10' >$$g1(0)</number>
<number name='g11' >$$g1(1)</number>
<number name='g1prime0' >$$g1prime(0)</number>
<number name='g1prime1' >$$g1prime(1)</number>
<number name='one' >1</number>
<number name='two' >2</number>
<number name='zero' >0</number>
<number name='three' >3</number>


<function name='g2' variables='t' >$$g(2,t)</function>
<function name='g2prime' variables='t' >$$gprime(2,t)</function>
<math name='L20' simplify="numbers">$$g(2,0)+$$g2prime(0)*(t-0)</math>
<math name='L21' simplify="numbers">$$g(2,1)+$$g2prime(1)*(t-1)</math>
<math name='L22' simplify="numbers">$$g(2,2)+$$g2prime(2)*(t-2)</math>
<number name='g20' >$$g(2,0)</number>
<number name='g2prime0' >$$g2prime(0)</number>
<number name='g21' >$$g(2,1)</number>
<number name='g2prime1' >$$g2prime(1)</number>
<number name='g22' >$$g(2,2)</number>
<number name='g2prime2' >$$g2prime(2)</number>
<math name='p20'>(0,$g20 )</math>
<math name='p21'>(1,$g21 )</math>
<math name='p22'>(2,$g22 )</math>
<math name='p10'>(0,$g10 )</math>
<math name='p11'>(1,$g11 )</math>

</setup>

We can find linear approximations of functions of different variables than <m>x</m>.  For example, let <m>g(t)=t^n e^{1-t}</m>, where <m>n</m> is some number.


<ol>

<li>
Let <m>n=1</m>, so <m>g(t)=</m> 
<answer>
<award>$g1 </award>
</answer>
 and <m>g'(t)=</m> 
<answer>
<award>$g1prime </award>
</answer>


<p>Find the equation for the tangent line of <m>g</m> at <m>t=0</m>.
</p>
<p>

<m>y=</m> 
<answer>
<award allowedErrorInNumbers='0.001'>$L10 </award>
</answer>
</p>

  
<p>Find the equation for the linear approximation of <m>g</m> around <m>t=1</m>
</p>
<p>

<m>L_{1}(t)=</m> 
<answer>
<award allowedErrorInNumbers='0.001'>$L11 </award>
</answer>
</p>

  <hint>
Linear approximation and tangent line are the same thing.  You should repeat the same calculations, once for <m>t=0</m> and once from <m>t=1</m>.

</hint>

<p>On the below graph of <m>g</m>, plot the tangent lines corresponding to these two linear approximations.</p>



<math hide name='px1'>3</math>
<math hide name='px2'>0.5</math>


<graph width='500' height='300' xmin='-2' xmax='7' ymin='-1' ymax='4' showNavigation='false'>

<copy tname='g1' />

<point hide name='snap1'>(0, $$g1(0))</point>
<point hide name='snap2'>(1, $$g1(1))</point>

<point stylenumber='2' name='tangentAnchor1' x='$px1' y='$$g1( $px1 )'>
<constraints>
  <attractTo>$snap1</attractTo>
  <attractTo>$snap2</attractTo>
  <constrainToGraph />
</constraints>
</point>
<line draggable='false' stylenumber='2' through='$tangentAnchor1' slope="$$g1prime( $(tangentAnchor1{prop='x'}) )" />

<point stylenumber='2' name='tangentAnchor2' x='$px2' y='$$g1( $px2 )' >
<constraints>
  <attractTo>$snap1</attractTo>
  <attractTo>$snap2</attractTo>
  <constrainToGraph />
</constraints>
</point>
<line draggable='false' stylenumber='2' through='$tangentAnchor2' slope="$$g1prime( $(tangentAnchor2{prop='x'}) )" />


</graph>

<answer>
<award matchPartial unorderedCompare><when>($px1, $px2) = (0, 1)</when></award>
</answer>



</li>

<li>
Let <m>n=2</m>, so <m>g(t)=</m> 
<answer>
<award>$g2 </award>
</answer>
 and <m>g'(t)=</m> 
<answer>
<award>$g2prime </award>
</answer>


